Here's how to implement all three requirements:

**1 & 2. Guard navigation with a confirmation dialog** — override `OnNavigating` in `AppShell.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop &&
        Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page &&
        page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

Key points: `GetDeferral()` is required for async checks, and `args.Cancel()` stops navigation.

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button** — in `EditProductPage.xaml`:

```xml
<ContentPage ...>
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

The `Command` fires instead of default back navigation, letting your ViewModel handle it:

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    if (HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes", "Discard changes?", "Discard", "Stay");
        if (!discard) return;
    }
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

> **Note:** Since `BackButtonBehavior.Command` bypasses the normal pop, the `OnNavigating` guard won't fire for the custom button — put the confirmation logic in the command itself. The `OnNavigating` guard still protects against swipe-back or hardware back button.
